      10 == root

public void printTreePreOrder(Node root) {
  if (root = null) {  // Base case
    return;
  }
  
  System.out.println(root.val);
  
  printTreePreOrder(root.left); // Case 1: try left first
  printTreePreOrder(root.right);  // Case 2: try right then
}

Pre-order: 10 5 2 7 15 12 20

Recursion v.s. DFS (Search Algorithm)

  • DFS, in more general scope, is one kind of search algorithm.
  • DFS can be implemented in an either recursive way, or in iterative way.

Back-tracking v.s. DFS

  • Back-tracking describes the behavior of DFS.

2 Depth-First Search (DFS)

Recall “using pre-order to traverse a tree”.

實現方法: easy to use recursion

常見考題:

  • Problem 1: Print all subsets of a set
  • Problem 2: Print all valid permutations of () () ()
    • ()()(), ((())), (())()
  • Problem 3: 凑硬幣金額 99 cents
    • 1 cent, 5 cents, 10 cents, 25 cents, given 99 cents, print all possible combinations
  • Problem 4 (set): (强化練習課)
    1. Given an input string = “127222458”, output all valid ip_address
      • 4 levels
    2. Permutation of a string (with/without duplicate letters)
      • str.length levels
    3. Permutation of all subsequence of a sorted string (allow set to have duplicate elements)
    4. Permutation of factors of a number
      • levels?
    5. How to randomly create a maze? (强化練習課)

DFS基本方法:

  1. How many levels in the recursion tree? What does it store on each level?
  2. How many different states should we try to put on each level?

2.1 Problem 1: Print All Subsets

Print all subsets of a set S = {“a”, “b”, “c”}

input = a x b x c
        0   0   0
        1   1   1
2 x 2 x 2 = 8
If S = {"a", "b", "b", "b", "c"}

input = a x b x c
        0   0   0
        1   1   1
            2
            3

DFS基本方法:

  1. How many levels in the recursion tree? What does it store on each level?
    • 3 elements, so 3 levels, and each level represents that one element (add or not add this element in the current level).
  2. How many different states should we try to put on each level?
    • Each element can have 2 states (ADD or NOT ADD)
char[] input: A B C
int index: 0 (by default)
void findSubset(char[] intput, int index, StringBuilder solutionPrefix) { // index: level of recursion
  // Base case: Print solution.
  if (index == input.length) {
    System.out.println(solutionPrefix);
    return;
  }
  
  // Case 1: Add input[index] to the solution prefix.
  solutionPrefix.append(input[index]);  // Add "A"
  findSubset(input, index + 1, solutionPrefix); // Breaking point...
  solutionPrefix.deleteCharAt(solutionPrefix.length - 1); // Remove "A"
  
  // Case 2: Do not add input[index] to the solution prefix.
  findSubset(input, index + 1, solutionPrefix);
}
  • Time: O(\(2^n\))
  • Space: O(\(\text{height}\)) = O(\(n\))

2.2 Problem 2: Find All Valid Permutations of Parentheses

Find all valid permutation using the parenthesis provided.

e.g.

Given ()()():
Some results:
- ((()))
- ()()()
- (())()

Mathematically, whenever we put a right parenthesis there is a left parenthesis to match it.

In more details, whenever we add a “)”, we must guarantee that the number of “(” added so far is larger than the number of “)” added so far.

DFS基本方法:

  1. How many levels in the recursion tree? What does it store on each level?
    • 6 levels, each level considers one position (in which there will be only one parenthesis added in this position).
  2. How many different states should we try to put on each level?
    • 2 branches, either put “(” OR put “)”

// n stores total number of "pair of ()" need to add. So total levels == 2 * n.
// l stores the number of left parenthesis "(" added so far.
// r stores the number of right parenthesis ")" added so far.
// soluPrefix: solution so far.
void DFS(int n = 3, int l = 0, int r = 0, StringBuilder soluPrefix) {
  // Base case
  if (l == n && r == n) {
    System.out.println(soluPrefix);
    return;
  }
  
  // Case 1: Add "(" on this level
  if (l < n) {
    soluPrefix.append('(');
    DFS(n, l + 1, r, soluPrefix);
    soluPrefix.deleteCharAt(soluPrefix.length() - 1);
  }
  
  // Case 2: Add ")" on this level
  if (l > r) {
    soluPrefix.append(')');
    DFS(n, l, r + 1, soluPrefix);
    soluPrefix.deleteCharAt(soluPrefix.length() - 1);
  }
}

Because there are \(2n\) levels in the recursion tree, and it is a binary tree, therefore there are at most \(2^{2n}\) nodes.

  • Time: O(\(2^{2n}\))
  • Space: O(\(2n\))

2.3 Problem 3: Print All Combinations of Coins

Print all combinations of coins that can sum up to a total value n.

e.g.
coin value = 25, 10, 5, 1

one possible way:
- 25 x 3
- 10 x 2
-  5 x 0
-  1 x 4

Solution 1:

DFS基本方法:

  1. How many levels in the recursion tree? What does it store on each level?
    • 4 levels, each level represents a coin value
  2. How many different states should we try to put on each level?
    • Dynamic changing
                          99
           /         |          |            \
25:       0          1          2            3
         r=99       r=74       r=49         r=24
       / |||| \     /||\       /||\         /||\
10:   0   ...  9    
     r=99 ... r=9


5:   ...


1:   ...

Because there are 4 levels, and each level AT MOST 99 branches.

  • Time: O(\(99^4\)) = O(\(n^4\))

Solution 2:

DFS基本方法:

  1. How many levels in the recursion tree? What does it store on each level?
    • Each level represents we take 1 coin out of the hand, max level is 99
  2. How many different states should we try to put on each level?
    • 4 branches: 25, 10, 5, 1
                       99
               /              \    \     \
L0:           25              10    5     1
             r=74            r=89  r=94  r=98
      /     |    |     \     /||\  /||\  /||\
L1:  25    10    5     1
    r=49  r=64  r=69  r=73

L2: ...


...


L98 (because we can at most take 99 times from the hand and each time we take 1 cent)
  • Time: O(\(4^{99}\))=O(\(4^n\))
          Solution 1    v.s.    Solution 2
Time        99^4       <<<<<      4^99
Space       O(4)                  O(99)

When n = 999999999999
Space       O(4)                O(999999999999)
                                Stack Overflow!
void findCombination(int[] coin, int moneyLeft = 99, int index, int[] sol) {
  if (index == 3) {
    sol[index] = moneyLeft;
    System.out.println(sol);
    return;
  }
  // money value on this level == coin[index]
  for (int i = 0; i <= moneyLeft / coin[index]; i++) {
    sol[index] = i;
    findCombination(coin, moneyLeft - i * coin[index], index + 1, sol);
  }
}

2.4 Problem 4: Print All Permutations of a String

Given a string with no duplicate letters, how to print out all permutations of the string.

e.g.

input = "ABC"
permutation:
- ABC
- ACB
- BAC
- BCA
- CAB
- CBA
              root (ABC)
         /         |         \
L0:  A(BC)       B(AC)       C(AB)
     /   \       /   \       /   \
L1: B(C)  C(B)  A(C)  C(A)  A(B)  B(A)
    |     |     |     |     |     |
L2: C     B     C     A     B     A

   ABC   ACB   BAC   BCA   CAB   CBA
  • Time: O(\(n!\))

New Version:

                     root (ABC)
          /              |               \
     swap(A, A)      swap(B, A)      swap(C, A)
L0:    A(*BC)          B(*AC)          C(*BA)
      /      \        /      \        /      \
    B<>B    C<>B    A<>A    C<>A    B<>B    A<>B
L1: B(**C)  C(**B)  A(**C)  C(**A)  A(**B)  B(**A)
    |       |       |       |       |       |
L2: C       B       C       A       B       A

   ABC     ACB     BAC     BCA     CAB     CBA
// index is the current layer that we are trying
void permutation(char[] input, int index) {
  // Base case: print solution and return.
  if (index == input.length) {
    System.out.println(input);
    return;
  }
  
  // Put each letter in the index-th position of the input string.
  for (int i = index; i < input.length; i++) {
    swap(input, index, i);
    permutation(input, index + 1);
    swap(input, index, i);
  }
}
  • Time: O(\(n!\))

Conclusion: Whenever every single permutation contains all elements in the initial input, then you should consider SWAP and SWAP.

3 Discussion

BFS1 v.s. DFS: Can we use BFS for permutation problems? Why?

  • 正確性: OK
  • Space: BFS1 can have a very large queue size because the recursion tree can grow exponentially.
